In the R.O.C.K. 'n' Learn program, children will have a safe, quiet space to complete distance learning while under the supervision of City of San Jose staff. Children will be responsible for bringing their own personal digital devices and headphones each day to complete distance learning. After completing distance learning, staff will offer enrichment, healthy recreation, developmental assets, homework assistance, safety, and fun afterschool care for children while ensuring CDC safety measures.

The R.O.C.K. 'n' Learn programs will be conducted in three week sessions with the next session starting on Monday, September 21st.

The R.O.C.K. n Learn Full day and Afterschool program is now FREE for families that qualify scholarship. All interested families that qualify for scholarship can contact myself at arlinda.duffy@sanjoseca.gov.

post_text: The State moved Santa Clara County into a lower level of risk today which is good news. Santa Clara County has its own SIP order which is stricter in some cases and supersedes the State. Stay tuned for more details.
shared_text:
County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
September 8 at 2:05 PM ·

Santa Clara County is at the Red Risk Level under the State’s new COVID-19 reopening framework. That means certain activities can resume, and certain businesses can reopen indoor operations at reduced capacity. Some indoor businesses and activities are still too high risk to allow at this time, however, and the local order and directives ensure that people who live in the county are protected from these risks. For example, movie theaters, indoor gatherings, and indoor dining are not yet permitted to reopen under Santa Clara County’s Order. Remember to follow the more restrictive set of rules. Continue to keep your distance, wear your mask, and get tested.

More details at https://direc.to/dsdf

Starting today, September 1st, Bascom Branch Library and Berryessa Branch Library have been added to the available Express Pickup locations, bringing the number of total locations up to 19!

Express Pickup is an easy, contactless, and convenient way to access the Library's physical collection while the interiors of our buildings remain closed to the public.

You can now even book an appointment to pick up your items ahead of time and there is even a way for you you request normally non-requestable children's items like picture books!

To learn more about this service visit https://www.sjpl.org/express-pickup. For answers to frequently asked questions about express pickup you can visit the Express Pickup FAQs Page.

post_text:
Together, we must denounce racism and racial discrimination in all its forms. There is much work to be done to ensure that all children, staff, and community members feel safe and acknowledged without racial bias in our schools, cities, and beyond.

Our district and education system can be an agent for change, right here within our schools. Through equitable educational experiences that instill students with awareness and lessons of kindness, humanity, and equality for every human being. We solidified that responsibility on June 18, 2020 when our Board of Trustees adopted Resolution No. 1358-06/20, Denouncing Racism and White Supremacy, and Supporting Equity, Wellbeing and Safety of Black People and that #BlackLivesMatter. Please visit our DEIB webpage for the entire letter to the community, the resolution and resources to fight racism. https://www.ogsd.net/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=586645&type=d&pREC_ID=1076023

post_text: A PG&E Public Safety Power Shutoff (PSPS) can occur during wildfire season but did you know that you may be at risk of a power shutoff even if you do not live in a high risk wildfire area? High temperatures, extreme dryness and record-high winds have created conditions in our state where any spark at the wrong time and place can lead to a major wildfire. If severe weather threatens a portion of the electric system, it may be necessary for PG&E to turn off electricity in the interest of public safety. Visit www.sccgov.org/PSPS for more PSPS preparedness tips.

County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
August 13 at 4:24 PM ·

HEAT WARNING: The US National Weather Service San Francisco Bay Area/Monterey California has issued an Excessive Heat Watch for the Santa Clara Valley starting Friday, Aug. 14 through Wednesday, Aug. 19, with above normal temperatures and afternoon highs in the mid-90s up to 103 degrees. Temperatures in Morgan Hill and Gilroy are expected to reach the low to mid-100 degrees. Cooling centers are open in Santa Clara County in the cities of Gilroy, San Jose, Mountain View, Cupertino, and Saratoga.

Social distancing guidelines will be enforced for cooling centers. For cooling center locations and heat safety tips (in English, Spanish, Vietnamese and Chinese), please visit https://bit.ly/heatsafetytipsSCC

post_text:
In an effort to facilitate online learning opportunities during Distance Learning, we are checking out Chromebooks for all students to use at home. Each school site sent a message about pickup days and times via ParentSquare.

Each student is eligible to receive one Chromebook. Students who picked up an Acer C740 Chromebook last year will continue to use those Chromebooks until the replacement Lenovo 500e can be issued. You will be notified when your Acer C740 can be exchanged for the Lenovo 500e.

By receiving a Chromebook you agree to the terms of the Device Loan Agreement (attached).

You can also optionally purchase insurance (flyer attached) to cover the device against theft, damage or loss.

By not picking up a device you are opting out of receiving a Chromebook for your student and are confirming that your child has adequate resources to participate in all instructional activities.

Our community is leading our first Social Distancing neighborhood cleanup this Saturday and looking for volunteers of ALL AGES 👨‍👨‍👧‍👦 to help for 1 hour of cleaning up 🧹 in and around Miner Park.

****************

July 13 at 5:54 PM ·

BREAKING: By order of the State, the County's Risk Reduction Health Officer Order (issued July 2) cannot go into effect as originally planned because the Governor of California took statewide action today to respond to the rapid and troubling growth of COVID-19 cases and hospitalizations across California. The State confirmed today that the following indoor operations need to close in Santa Clara County by 12:01 a.m. on Wednesday, July 15 : fitness centers, places of worship, indoor protests, offices for non-critical infrastructure sectors, personal care services, hair salons and barbershops, and malls. As many know, there have been allegations that a District employee was involved in a videotaped incident in which the person appeared to have intentionally coughed on a baby at a local Yogurtland. We want to inform our community that the District employee who was alleged to have engaged in this conduct is no longer an employee of our District. The Oak Grove School District’s highest priority is the safety of our students and the well-being of all of the children in the community we serve. We do not tolerate conduct from any employee that compromises any child’s safety. As we welcome our students back for learning this summer and in the fall in these unprecedented times, the District’s commitment to creating and maintaining a safe environment for our students is unwavering.

Oak Grove School District

The Oak Grove School District’s highest priority is the safety of our students. We do not tolerate conduct from any employee that compromises any child’s safety. We are aware of an incident allegedly involving one of our employees who was videotaped coughing on a baby at a local eatery. The employee is currently off of work and not providing any services to our District students. This matter is under investigation by the San Jose Police Department and we want to reassure you that the District is cooperating with the law enforcement authorities. Because this matter is the subject of an ongoing police investigation, we are not able to comment further on this matter.

Jose L. Manzo, Superintendent

post_text: The Covid-19 Pandemic has brought many challenges to Oak Grove School District (OGSD), particularly to four Title 1 schools located in San Jose’s Council District 2. Christopher Elementary, Stipe Elementary, Edenvale Elementary, and Davis Intermediate. Superintendent Jose Manzo partnered with District 2 City Council Member Sergio Jimenez to get support from the City of San Jose for the purchase of 210 Lenovo 500e Gen 2 Chromebooks for students. These devices will be used to bridge the digital divide in our community! Thank you for the support.

DEADLINE EXTENDED TO JULY 15, 2020 -- Application window NOW OPEN if you need help buying food while schools are closed. Visit: https://ca.p-ebt.org or call the P-EBT Customer Service line at 877-328-9677. Apply before July 15, 2020 (extended from June 30).

OVERVIEW: Due to Coronavirus (COVID-19), children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals at school will get extra food benefits. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT benefits. P-EBT benefits help families in California buy food when schools are closed because of the coronavirus emergency.

Families will get up to $365 per eligible child on their P-EBT card to use on food and groceries.

Families with children who get CalFresh, Medi-Cal or Foster Care benefits do not need to apply. Most should have received their P-EBT card in the mail during the month of May.

Families with children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals and who did not get their P-EBT card in the mail by the end of May must apply online before July 15, 2020. Apply at https://ca.p-ebt.org.

shared_text:
County of Santa Clara Public Health Department is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
June 3 at 11:30 AM ·

Santa Clara County has made huge steps forward in our fight against COVID-19. The data shows that as result of all of everyone’s hard work to social distance and stay home, we are able to ease more restrictions. Please remember that this does not mean the pandemic is over. It means that we have successfully slowed the spread of the virus. Updates to the Shelter-in-Place Order that allow for more businesses and activities will begin Friday, June 5. With these changes we must continue to wear face coverings, wash our hands frequently, avoid touching our nose, eyes and mouth, and keep a minimum of six feet between ourselves and people we do not live with. Take a look at what’s opening up!

• Businesses
• Education and childcare
• All childcare, summer camps, and summer school
• Outdoor: ceremonies, religious gatherings, and recreation

For a summary of changes, visit: https://direc.to/egNi and list of everything that’s allowed, visit https://direc.to/egNf

San José Virtual Recreation Center Information

The Virtual Recreation Center from the City of San José’s Department of Parks, Recreation, and Neighborhood Services (PRNS) provides free online educational and recreational resources for families during the shelter-in-place. This includes ways to socially connect through livestream leisure classes; videos to explore beloved PRNS destinations like Happy Hollow Park & Zoo; creative outlets in cooking, drawing and making music; and activities to care for your physical and mental health through exercise, sports and guided meditation. Visit the City's Virtual Recreation Center for daily activities and over a hundred fun resources:
https://www.sanjoseca.gov/your-government/departments-offices/parks-recreation-neighborhood-services/virtual-recreation-center

post_text:
San Jose launches "Great Plates Delivered"

Participant Eligibility Requirements

Must be 65 or older or high-risk. High-risk includes those who are COVID-19 positive, COVID-19 exposed as documented by a public health official or medical professional or individuals with an underlying condition
Must live alone or with one (1) program-eligible adult; must not be currently receiving assistance from other federal nutrition assistance programs
Receive no more than $74,940 in income for a household of one (1) and $101,460 for a household of two (2), this equates to 600% of the federal poverty limit
Must affirm an inability to prepare or obtain meals

text:
Shout out to
OGSD CNS department, thank you for all you do to keep the community fed!

San José Parks, Recreation and Neighborhood Services
May 19 at 1:00 PM ·

#SVStrongSchoolHeroes and #SVFoodBosses across County of Santa Clara, California have been diligently working every day since school closures helping prepare meals. Moreland School District, Luther Burbank School, Lakeside Joint School District, Orchard School District, Alum Rock Union Elementary School District, Oak Grove School District, and Union School District have all been coordinating efforts with their kitchen teams to ensure all families and communities have meals on a daily basis. Thank you for all you do! #SiliconValleyStrong #ClassifiedSchoolEmployeesWeek Santa Clara County Office of Education

Cindy Chavez
April 17 at 8:09 PM ·

In addition to first responders and health workers, there are many more essential workers who are risking exposure to COVID-19 everyday so the rest of us can stay home and stay healthy. This weekend we should give all our essential workers a big round of applause.

On Sunday at 5 pm, open a window or stand in front of your house and clap, cheer, ring a bell, or bang pots and pans together for two minutes to salute our doctors, nurses, first responders, pharmacists, grocery workers, restaurant workers, delivery drivers, postal employees, janitors, restaurant employees, and every other essential employee.

Don't forget to practice social distancing during the round of applause, but do take photos or video and post them on social media with the hashtag #ClapBecauseWeCareSCC so our essential workers will know how much you support and appreciate them.

State Superintendent Tony Thurmond and the CDE are extremely concerned about the mental health and wellness of students whose lives have dramatically changed during the COVID-19 response, as well as the health of staff who are also coping with these changes.

To support students, schools, and communities during this challenging time, the CDE has gathered information regarding mental health resources, including links for students to get direct access to mental health professionals. The new “Help for Students in Crisis” web page includes crisis and warm line numbers, along with other COVID-19-related resources for providing virtual mental health services, and information for mental health providers, families, and youth: https://www.cde.ca.gov/ls/cg/mh/studentcrisishelp.asp.

OGSD’s new printed FLO packets (Flexible Learning Options) will be available at our new locations: Anderson, Christopher, Davis, Hayes and Herman on Wednesday 4/8 and Thursday 4/9 from 10am until 12pm. There will be one packet per grade level with a combination of reading and math learning options. This packet is meant to sustain students through May 1st.

These FLOs are optional and will not be scored for a grade. If your child has an IEP (Individual Educational Plan) and you are not sure of their academic grade level, feel free to contact the Special Education Department at 408-227-8300.

Free breakfast and lunch meals for children ages 0-18 are still being provided Monday through Friday at Anderson, Christopher, Davis, Edenvale, Hayes and Stipe from 10:30am - 11:30am, children do not need to be present.

post_text: Communities working together!
shared_text:
Jennifer Zenk is with Erin State and 3 others at Oak Grove School District.
March 26 at 6:25 PM · San Jose, CA ·

We want to give a BIG THANK YOU to the Oak Grove School District for donating disinfectant wipes, purell hand sanitizer, gloves and masks to Good Samaritan Hospital. Many thanks to Ledesma, Anderson, Baldwin, Herman, Hayes, Oak Ridge and Sakamoto Schools!!! Thank you, Jeff and Erin State for thinking of how they could help the critical healthcare providers. Thank you, Laura Rodrigues Meusel (Oak Grove District Community Outreach Coordinator) and Ivan Chaides (Assistant Superintendent) from Oak Grove School District for making this happen. Finally, a warm thank you to all the principals and teachers that helped facilitate this effort! It is greatly needed and greatly appreciated. Your generosity is beyond amazing and is a great reflection of our community strength!!!

Thank you,

Jennifer Zenk, frontline ICU RN, Good Samaritan Hospital
Kimberly Reeves, Pre-Op, RN, Good Samaritan Hospital

And thank you from all the staff at Good Samaritan Hospital!!!

Thank you, Laura Rodrigues Meusel (Oak Grove District Community Outreach Coordinator) and Ivan Chaides (Assistant Superintendent) from Oak Grove School District for making this happen. Finally, a warm thank you to all the principals and teachers that helped facilitate this effort! It is greatly needed and greatly appreciated. Your generosity is beyond amazing and is a great reflection of our community strength!!!

Thank you,

Jennifer Zenk, frontline ICU RN, Good Samaritan Hospital
Kimberly Reeves, Pre-Op, RN, Good Samaritan Hospital

And thank you from all the staff at Good Samaritan Hospital!!!

UPDATE from SCCPHD Regarding COVID-19 Reporting.
Community transmission is ongoing in Santa Clara County. As the community follows the Health Officer Order to Shelter in Place issued on March 16, 2020, notification regarding potential contacts to cases will no longer be provided, and school districts are not required to provide any notifications. Everyone, except for those providing or receiving essential services, should be staying home, especially anyone who is feeling ill. Anyone who develops symptoms of COVID-19, should call their healthcare provider for further guidance before going to the doctor. Only the severely ill should seek care at an emergency room and should, if at all possible, call first.

As our community navigates through the impact of COVID-19 and the rapidly changing guidance from the Public Health Department and the Center for Disease Control, Santa Clara County Office of Education’s Inclusion Collaborative has expanded its Inclusion Support WarmLine Services.

Support will be provided by answering questions, addressing concerns and providing social stories to support children’s understanding of ‘social distancing’, etc. Also available will be alternative educational resources, support for flexible learning and addressing individual needs for children with IEPs. Visual Support, individual schedules, etc. are also available. Call (408) 453-6651 or email WarmLineRemoteLearning@sccoe.org.

Starting Monday March 16, 2020, OGSD CNS department will be distributing free meals to all children under the age of 18 at six school sites: Anderson, Davis, Christopher, Edenvale, Hayes, and Stipe.

During the school closure all children under the age of 18 can pick up a free breakfast and lunch sack during the hours of service from 10:30 am - 11:30 am Monday through Friday at one of the locations above.

CNS department will have convenient drive-through pick up or walk up service for meals to take home. We look forward to providing this service to all children in the community during this school closure to ensure children have access to healthy meals in our community.

post_text: 2020 Census: Subject to further guidance from the County's Public Health Office, the City is postponing Census-related community events for the next 30 days. Residents can now complete the 2020 Census online at www.my2020census.gov or by telephone at 844-330-2020. In addition to English, Spanish and Vietnamese, the online survey and phone service are available in many additional languages. Assistance completing the Census is available at City library branches. Everyone living in the United States is encouraged to participate in the census regardless of age, gender, immigration or housing situation. The 2020 Census does not include questions about citizenship or immigration status, and is completely confidential.

post_text: To stay updated please follow the Santa Clara County Public Health Department.
shared_text:
County of Santa Clara Public Health Department was live.
January 31 at 2:55 PM ·

Update: Dr. Cody addressing news media about novel Coronavirus.

This is the first confirmed case of novel coronavirus in Santa Clara County and the Bay Area. Since we are a large county and many of our residents travel frequently for business and personal reasons, we are not surprised to be announcing this case and we have been preparing for weeks for this possibility. Preventing and controlling the spread of infectious diseases is what local public health departments are built to do, it is one of our core functions. We are in full swing. The current case is in home isolation and being monitored by our Public Health staff. Home isolation means the person does not leave their home for specified duration of time. If family or loved ones are unable to provide food and needed items, our Public Health Department will provide them. We have an FAQ and updated info available on our website to help answer questions: http://sccphd.org/coronavirus

So...what is the #2020Census?

1. It is a survey with only 9 questions.
2. It will NOT include a question about citizenship status.
3. It determines California’s federal funding for important community services that help support our families, and ensures fair representation of California in Washington D.C

Learn more here: https://californiacensus.org/

#CaliforniaForAll

post_text: We were pleased with all the community that came out last night!
shared_text:
Councilmember Sergio Jimenez
January 24 at 1:45 PM ·

When I have the opportunity to speak to Oak Grove School District Elementary School students -- at a City Hall Tour, College Day, or a visit to their school auditorium -- they often have NO idea who I am.

But then I ask them if they like to play at their neighborhood park, if they like going to their neighborhood library, if they take walks on City streets, if they notice new buildings, if they love waving to our San Jose Police Officers and Firefighters… and everyone raises their hands.

I tell them that those are all services made possible by the City of San Jose. And I, as their representative and voice at City Hall, help support these services and make decisions that make our neighborhoods a cleaner, safer, more inclusive place for everyone.

I can’t do this alone. Thank you to all the students, families, educators, administrators, and Board Members at OGSD's State of the District last night for listening to my #SJD2 update and for continuing to engage with the City to make our home a better place!

Happy 90th day of school today! This marks the half-way point of the 2019-2020 school year, which is hard to believe.

All schools will be closed in observance on Monday, January 20th for Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Day. Schools are also closed on Tuesday, January 21st for a teacher in-service day. Classes resume on Wednesday, January 22nd.

For our elementary families, conferences begin next week for some students - a reminder that all elementary schools will be on early release 1/22 through 1/31. For our middle school students, the new semester begins on Wednesday, January 22nd.

The Indigo Program is a program option for grades K-8 located on the Frost Elementary School Campus. Our success depends on parents committed to our educational philosophy and are passionate about volunteering in the classroom each week.

Every family applying to the Indigo Program should first come to an Open House. It's the best way to see Indigo in action! Open Houses offer complete campus and classroom tours, followed by a presentation from our principal, staff members, and students. All Open Houses begin in the cafeteria. Indigo is a K-8 program option open to all.

Indigo Program Open Houses & Tours
text:
The Indigo Program is a program option for grades K-8 located on the Frost Elementary School Campus. Our success depends on parents committed to our educational philosophy and are passionate about volunteering in the classroom each week.

Every family applying to the Indigo Program should first come to an Open House. It's the best way to see Indigo in action! Open Houses offer complete campus and classroom tours, followed by a presentation from our principal, staff members, and students. All Open Houses begin in the cafeteria. Indigo is a K-8 program option open to all.

post_text: Applications for Oak Grove's Program Options begin Monday, January 13th. One of our programs is AdVENTURE STEM, an award-winning California Distinguished School that serves 268 students in grades 5-8 on the Herman Intermediate Campus. 4th grade students who are interested in learning more can sign-up for a tour and/or visit the open house. For more details please go to www.adventurestem.org.

post_text:
Oscar Ortiz, attended the KNBR Step Up to the Plate Education Reception and was awarded $1,000 for The Academy!

"Our school, The Academy, is a community day school for at risk 8th graders who have been removed from their home school as an intervention. We meet weekly with our 3rd grade “little buddies” to develop leadership skills. We would like to chaperone our little buddies, who attend a Title I school, to the San Jose Museum of Art for K-12 Guided Tour on December 12th. Their school has just adopted a Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts and Math (STEAM) focus, and we would like to help reinforce the artistic component of the program. We are requesting money for the tour admission for 38 students, school bus, as quoted by our Transportation
department. Thank you very much for your time and consideration.”
